                "name": "David Boyd Mercer",
                "href": "/profile/David-Boyd-Mercer"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes. Ch can have multiple pronunciations, generally corresponding to when the words entered the language. The oldest ch words are generally pronounced with a hard k sound, as they were being pronounced in Latin at the time. Christian words, such as Christ and Christmas are examples of this, but also ache, school, and stomach.Words that entered in the late Old English period and Middle English period generally have the traditional ch sound. Words like church, cheese, and much. (Note that you will sometimes see old documents spelling and pronouncing church \u201ckirke,\u201d with the hard k sound. Also, fun little trivia, the English word cheese and the Spanish word queso are cognate, both originating from the original Vandal word.)Words that entered English from French in the modern period, typically pronounce the ch as the much softer sh, such as machine, champagne, and charade.This \u201ctime rule\u201d is a generalization, and there are many, many exceptions. ",
