            },
            "answer_text": "Yes quite a few. Chicago comes to mind, so does brochure, parachute really any <ch> word borrowed from the French language as opposed to Norman French. It is difficult to tell which French-looking words came from which French language, but words like cherry are from Norman French and have the [t\u0283] sound, while words from modern French like chateau have the [\u0283] sound. Additionally, a few words from Norman French like chemise used to have the /t\u0283/ sound but then became France-Frenchified in the 1800s and now have the [\u0283] sound. The dominant language of France lost the distinction between /\u0283/ and /t\u0283/ after Norman French stopped being spoon as a native language in England. Once France became a world power and Parisian French was the dominant dialect, English speakers began speaking French with closer to Parisian pronunciations and began pronouncing some French words that way too, even if the words were older than Parisian French\u2019s status as the dominant dialect. ",
